arch:property.oc:show_val: Phase X: Site abandonment after major collapse dating to the Byzantine period from the CE 4th to 5th c. New drainage systems are installed including that associated with the newly built west precinct wall.
0.56 m north south -by- 4.75 m east west.
Full blockage, robbing out and dumping.

Locus 50 is the south bench resting on dirt (Locus 53) just above the floor of the covered pool, against the south section of Locus 58 (the north, west, and east walls surrounding the covered pool). It is a poorly constructed bench, consisting of six main dressed ashlars and a few smaller hewn stones. The stones are rather haphazardly dry-laid into one row. The purpose of this bench is quite unclear (hence the quotation marks around the term!). Its poor construction is far inferior to the main bath construction and even the raised floor (Locus 49) on which it rests. It may have served to shore up Locus 58, which it abuts, if that wall had been weakened. Alternatively, it could have served as a bench or shelf, perhaps for industrial storage of some kind. Later than the floor on which it rests, Locus 50 is phased to Stage 5, a period of blockage and dumping.
